Security Operations Fundamentals > [T2]: Using Machine and Deep Learning for Security

User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) Platforms

Modern organizations face thousands of threats daily, and traditional detection techniques have become ineffective. Researchers and security professionals are trying to develop new concepts, prototypes, or models to solve the issue of the overwhelming amount of data processed every day. Some of these solutions are Machine learning and Deep Learning.

Artificial intelligence (AI) is the art of making computer programs behave like a human, and by behaving, we mean perceiving, learning, understanding, and knowing. AI involves diverse areas such as computer science, neuroscience, psychology, etc.

Machine learning is the study and creation of algorithms that learn from given data and examples. It is a particular approach to artificial intelligence. Many security vendors started to adopt machine learning techniques in their security products to defend against modern and complex cyber-attacks, and now thousands of security products include Machine learning models to enhance threat detection.

Examples of ML uses in security are:

  • Detect Network Anomalies.
  • Detect unknown Malware.
  • Detect advanced persistent threats.


Deep Learning is a sub-field of machine learning concerned with algorithms inspired by the structure and function of the brain. In other words, using a complex structure of algorithms modeled on the human brain. 

The application of ML in security is represented by a new line of security products called User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) platforms. The platforms use machine learning and, in particular, deep learning models to analyze daily records to detect malicious activities such as account compromise, lateral movement, and data exfiltration.

 

Figure - zoom in

Usually, UEBA comes as a SIEM component rather than a standalone solution. The SIEM is where all data is collected, making it the perfect place to host a UEBA.
